<p></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="rellink relarticle mainarticle">Main article: <a href="/wiki/History_of_Bali" title="History of Bali">History of Bali</a></div>
<p>Bali was inhabited by around 2000 BC by <a href="/wiki/Austronesian_people" title="Austronesian people" class="mw-redirect">Austronesian people</a> who migrated originally from <a href="/wiki/Southeast_Asia" title="Southeast Asia">Southeast Asia</a> and <a href="/wiki/Oceania" title="Oceania">Oceania</a> through <a href="/wiki/Maritime_Southeast_Asia" title="Maritime Southeast Asia">Maritime Southeast Asia</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Hinzler_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Hinzler-8"><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup> Culturally and linguistically, the Balinese are thus closely related to the people of the Indonesian archipelago, Malaysia, the Philippines, and Oceania.<sup id="cite_ref-Hinzler_8-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Hinzler-8"><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup> Stone tools dating from this time have been found near the village of Cekik in the island's west.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9"><span>[</span>9<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Lonely_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Lonely-10"><span>[</span>10<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>In ancient Bali, nine Hindu sects existed, namely Pasupata, Bhairawa, Siwa Shidanta, Waisnawa, Bodha, Brahma, Resi, Sora and Ganapatya. Each sect revered a specific deity as its personal Godhead.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11"><span>[</span>11<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Balinese culture was strongly influenced by Indian, Chinese, and particularly <a href="/wiki/Hindu" title="Hindu">Hindu</a> culture, beginning around the 1st century AD. The name <i>Bali dwipa</i> ("Bali island") has been discovered from various inscriptions, including the Blanjong pillar inscription written by <a href="/wiki/Sri_Kesari_Warmadewa" title="Sri Kesari Warmadewa">Sri Kesari Warmadewa</a> in 914 AD and mentioning "Walidwipa". It was during this time that the complex irrigation system <i><a href="/wiki/Subak_(irrigation)" title="Subak (irrigation)">subak</a></i> was developed to grow rice. Some religious and cultural traditions still in existence today can be traced back to this period. The Hindu <a href="/wiki/Majapahit_Empire" title="Majapahit Empire" class="mw-redirect">Majapahit Empire</a> (12931520 AD) on eastern <a href="/wiki/Java_(island)" title="Java (island)" class="mw-redirect">Java</a> founded a Balinese colony in 1343. When the empire declined, there was an exodus of intellectuals, artists, priests, and musicians from Java to Bali in the 15th century.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Balinese_sculpture_with_umbrella.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f2/Balinese_sculpture_with_umbrella.JPG/170px-Balinese_sculpture_with_umbrella.JPG" width="170" height="227" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f2/Balinese_sculpture_with_umbrella.JPG/255px-Balinese_sculpture_with_umbrella.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f2/Balinese_sculpture_with_umbrella.JPG/340px-Balinese_sculpture_with_umbrella.JPG 2x"></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Balinese_sculpture_with_umbrella.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.23wmf6/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt=""></a></div>
At religious festivals on Bali the sculptures get dressed up and umbrellas are placed by the temples.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The first <a href="/wiki/European_ethnic_groups" title="European ethnic groups" class="mw-redirect">European</a> contact with Bali is thought to have been made in 1585 when a <a href="/wiki/Portugal" title="Portugal">Portuguese</a> ship foundered off the <a href="/wiki/Bukit_Peninsula" title="Bukit Peninsula">Bukit Peninsula</a> and left a few Portuguese in the service of <a href="/wiki/Dewa_Agung" title="Dewa Agung">Dewa Agung</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12"><span>[</span>12<span>]</span></a></sup> In 1597 the Dutch explorer <a href="/wiki/Cornelis_de_Houtman" title="Cornelis de Houtman">Cornelis de Houtman</a> arrived at Bali and, with the establishment of the <a href="/wiki/Dutch_East_India_Company" title="Dutch East India Company">Dutch East India Company</a> in 1602, the stage was set for colonial control two and a half centuries later when Dutch control expanded across the Indonesian archipelago throughout the second half of the 19th century (see <a href="/wiki/Dutch_East_Indies" title="Dutch East Indies">Dutch East Indies</a>). Dutch political and economic control over Bali began in the 1840s on the island's north coast, when the Dutch pitted various distrustful Balinese realms against each other.<sup id="cite_ref-ctpqur_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ctpqur-13"><span>[</span>13<span>]</span></a></sup> In the late 1890s, struggles between Balinese kingdoms in the island's south were exploited by the Dutch to increase their control.</p>
<p>The Dutch mounted large naval and ground <a href="/wiki/Dutch_intervention_in_Bali_(1906)" title="Dutch intervention in Bali (1906)">assaults at the Sanur region</a> in 1906 and were met by the thousands of members of the royal family and their followers who fought against the superior Dutch force in a suicidal <i><a href="/wiki/Puputan" title="Puputan">puputan</a></i> defensive assault rather than face the humiliation of surrender.<sup id="cite_ref-ctpqur_13-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ctpqur-13"><span>[</span>13<span>]</span></a></sup> Despite Dutch demands for surrender, an estimated 200 Balinese marched to their death against the invaders.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14"><span>[</span>14<span>]</span></a></sup> In the <a href="/wiki/Dutch_intervention_in_Bali_(1908)" title="Dutch intervention in Bali (1908)">Dutch intervention in Bali (1908)</a>, a similar massacre occurred in the face of a Dutch assault in <a href="/wiki/Klungkung" title="Klungkung" class="mw-redirect">Klungkung</a>. Afterwards the Dutch governors were able to exercise administrative control over the island, but local control over religion and culture generally remained intact. Dutch rule over Bali came later and was never as well established as in other parts of Indonesia such as Java and <a href="/wiki/Maluku_Islands" title="Maluku Islands">Maluku</a>.</p>
<p>In the 1930s, anthropologists <a href="/wiki/Margaret_Mead" title="Margaret Mead">Margaret Mead</a> and <a href="/wiki/Gregory_Bateson" title="Gregory Bateson">Gregory Bateson</a>, and artists <a href="/wiki/Miguel_Covarrubias" title="Miguel Covarrubias">Miguel Covarrubias</a> and <a href="/wiki/Walter_Spies" title="Walter Spies">Walter Spies</a>, and musicologist <a href="/wiki/Colin_McPhee" title="Colin McPhee">Colin McPhee</a> created a western image of Bali as "an enchanted land of <a href="/wiki/Aesthetics" title="Aesthetics">aesthetes</a> at peace with themselves and nature", and western tourism first developed on the island.<sup id="cite_ref-Friend_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Friend-15"><span>[</span>15<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Balinese_dancers.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Balinese_dancers.jpg/170px-Balinese_dancers.jpg" width="170" height="253" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Balinese_dancers.jpg/255px-Balinese_dancers.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Balinese_dancers.jpg/340px-Balinese_dancers.jpg 2x"></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Balinese_dancers.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.23wmf6/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt=""></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Balinese_dance" title="Balinese dance">Balinese dancers</a> show for tourists, in <a href="/wiki/Ubud" title="Ubud">Ubud</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><a href="/wiki/Imperial_Japan" title="Imperial Japan" class="mw-redirect">Imperial Japan</a> occupied Bali during World War II. Bali Island was not originally a target in their Netherlands East Indies Campaign, but as the airfields on <a href="/wiki/Borneo" title="Borneo">Borneo</a> were inoperative due to heavy rains the <a href="/wiki/Imperial_Japanese_Army" title="Imperial Japanese Army">Imperial Japanese Army</a> decided to occupy Bali, which did not suffer from comparable weather. The island had no regular <a href="/wiki/Royal_Netherlands_East_Indies_Army" title="Royal Netherlands East Indies Army">Royal Netherlands East Indies Army</a> (KNIL) troops. There was only a Native Auxiliary Corps <i>Prajoda</i> (Korps Prajoda) consisting of about 600 native soldiers and several Dutch KNIL officers under command of KNIL Lieutenant Colonel W.P. Roodenburg. On 19 February 1942 the Japanese forces landed near the town of Senoer [Senur]. The island was quickly captured.<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16"><span>[</span>16<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>During the Japanese occupation a Balinese military officer, <a href="/wiki/I_Gusti_Ngurah_Rai" title="I Gusti Ngurah Rai">Gusti Ngurah Rai</a>, formed a Balinese 'freedom army'. The lack of institutional changes from the time of Dutch rule however, and the harshness of war requisitions made Japanese rule worse than the Dutch one.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17"><span>[</span>17<span>]</span></a></sup> Following Japan's Pacific surrender in August 1945, the Dutch promptly returned to Indonesia, including Bali, immediately to reinstate their pre-war colonial administration. This was resisted by the Balinese rebels now using Japanese weapons. On 20 November 1946, the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Battle_of_Marga&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Battle of Marga (page does not exist)">Battle of Marga</a> was fought in Tabanan in central Bali. Colonel I Gusti Ngurah Rai, by then 29 years old, finally rallied his forces in east Bali at Marga Rana, where they made a <a href="/wiki/Suicide_attack" title="Suicide attack">suicide attack</a> on the heavily armed Dutch. The Balinese battalion was entirely wiped out, breaking the last thread of Balinese military resistance. In 1946 the Dutch constituted Bali as one of the 13 administrative districts of the newly proclaimed <a href="/wiki/State_of_East_Indonesia" title="State of East Indonesia">State of East Indonesia</a>, a rival state to the Republic of Indonesia which was proclaimed and headed by <a href="/wiki/Sukarno" title="Sukarno">Sukarno</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mohammad_Hatta" title="Mohammad Hatta">Hatta</a>. Bali was included in the "Republic of the United States of Indonesia" when the Netherlands recognised Indonesian independence on 29 December 1949.</p>
<p>The 1963 eruption of <a href="/wiki/Mount_Agung" title="Mount Agung">Mount Agung</a> killed thousands, created economic havoc and forced many displaced Balinese to be <i><a href="/wiki/Transmigration_program" title="Transmigration program">transmigrated</a></i> to other parts of Indonesia. Mirroring the widening of social divisions across Indonesia in the 1950s and early 1960s, Bali saw conflict between supporters of the traditional <a href="/wiki/Caste_system" title="Caste system" class="mw-redirect">caste system</a>, and those rejecting these traditional values. Politically, the opposition was represented by supporters of the <a href="/wiki/Indonesian_Communist_Party" title="Indonesian Communist Party" class="mw-redirect">Indonesian Communist Party</a> (PKI) and the <a href="/wiki/Indonesian_Nationalist_Party" title="Indonesian Nationalist Party" class="mw-redirect">Indonesian Nationalist Party</a> (PNI), with tensions and ill-feeling further increased by the PKI's land reform programs.<sup id="cite_ref-ctpqur_13-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ctpqur-13"><span>[</span>13<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/30_September_Movement" title="30 September Movement">An attempted coup</a> in Jakarta was put down by forces led by General Suharto. The army became the dominant power as it instigated <a href="/wiki/Indonesian_killings_of_1965%E2%80%9366" title="Indonesian killings of 196566">a violent anti-communist purge</a>, in which the army blamed the PKI for the coup. Most estimates suggest that at least 500,000 people were killed across Indonesia, with an estimated 80,000 killed in Bali, equivalent to 5% of the island's population.<sup id="cite_ref-ctpqur_13-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ctpqur-13"><span>[</span>13<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Friend_15-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Friend-15"><span>[</span>15<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Ricklefs_18-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Ricklefs-18"><span>[</span>18<span>]</span></a></sup> With no Islamic forces involved as in Java and Sumatra, upper-caste PNI landlords led the extermination of PKI members.<sup id="cite_ref-Ricklefs_18-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Ricklefs-18"><span>[</span>18<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>As a result of the 1965/66 upheavals, Suharto was able to manoeuvre Sukarno <a href="/wiki/Transition_to_the_New_Order" title="Transition to the New Order">out of the presidency</a>, and his <a href="/wiki/New_Order_(Indonesia)" title="New Order (Indonesia)">"New Order"</a> government reestablished relations with western countries. The pre-War Bali as "paradise" was revived in a modern form, and the resulting large growth in tourism has led to a dramatic increase in Balinese standards of living and significant foreign exchange earned for the country.<sup id="cite_ref-ctpqur_13-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ctpqur-13"><span>[</span>13<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/2002_Bali_bombings" title="2002 Bali bombings">A bombing in 2002</a> by militant <a href="/wiki/Islamist" title="Islamist" class="mw-redirect">Islamists</a> in the tourist area of <a href="/wiki/Kuta" title="Kuta">Kuta</a> killed 202 people, mostly foreigners. This attack, and <a href="/wiki/2005_Bali_bombings" title="2005 Bali bombings">another in 2005</a>, severely affected tourism, bringing much economic hardship to the island.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Geography">Geography</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Geography">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="rellink boilerplate seealso">See also: <a href="/wiki/List_of_bodies_of_water_in_Bali" title="List of bodies of water in Bali">List of bodies of water in Bali</a>&nbsp;and <a href="/wiki/List_of_mountains_in_Bali" title="List of mountains in Bali">List of mountains in Bali</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Bali_Labeled.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/Bali_Labeled.png/220px-Bali_Labeled.png" width="220" height="160" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/Bali_Labeled.png/330px-Bali_Labeled.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/Bali_Labeled.png/440px-Bali_Labeled.png 2x"></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Bali_Labeled.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.23wmf6/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt=""></a></div>
Topography of the island</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The island of Bali lies 3.2&nbsp;km (2&nbsp;mi) east of <a href="/wiki/Java_(island)" title="Java (island)" class="mw-redirect">Java</a>, and is approximately <a href="/wiki/8th_parallel_south" title="8th parallel south">8 degrees south</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Equator" title="Equator">equator</a>. Bali and Java are separated by the <a href="/wiki/Bali_Strait" title="Bali Strait">Bali Strait</a>. East to west, the island is approximately 153&nbsp;km (95&nbsp;mi) wide and spans approximately 112&nbsp;km (69&nbsp;mi) north to south; administratively it covers 5,780 km<sup>2</sup>, or 5,577 km<sup>2</sup> without <a href="/wiki/Nusa_Penida" title="Nusa Penida">Nusa Penida</a> District,<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19"><span>[</span>19<span>]</span></a></sup> its population density is roughly 750 people/km<sup>2</sup>.</p>
<p>Bali's central mountains include several peaks over 3,000 metres in elevation. The highest is <a href="/wiki/Mount_Agung" title="Mount Agung">Mount Agung</a> (3,031 m), known as the "mother mountain" which is an active <a href="/wiki/Volcano" title="Volcano">volcano</a>. Mountains range from centre to the eastern side, with Mount Agung the easternmost peak. Bali's volcanic nature has contributed to its exceptional fertility and its tall mountain ranges provide the high rainfall that supports the highly productive agriculture sector. South of the mountains is a broad, steadily descending area where most of Bali's large rice crop is grown. The northern side of the mountains slopes more steeply to the sea and is the main coffee producing area of the island, along with rice, vegetables and cattle. The longest river, <a href="/wiki/Ayung_River" title="Ayung River">Ayung River</a>, flows approximately 75&nbsp;km.</p>
<p>The island is surrounded by <a href="/wiki/Coral_reefs" title="Coral reefs" class="mw-redirect">coral reefs</a>. Beaches in the south tend to have white sand while those in the north and west have <a href="/wiki/Black_sand" title="Black sand">black sand</a>. Bali has no major waterways, although the Ho River is navigable by small <i><a href="/wiki/Sampan" title="Sampan">sampan</a></i> boats. Black sand beaches between Pasut and Klatingdukuh are being developed for tourism, but apart from the seaside temple of <a href="/wiki/Tanah_Lot" title="Tanah Lot">Tanah Lot</a>, they are not yet used for significant tourism.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:1_Tegalalang_rice_terrace_ubud_bali.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/1_Tegalalang_rice_terrace_ubud_bali.jpg/220px-1_Tegalalang_rice_terrace_ubud_bali.jpg" width="220" height="102" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/1_Tegalalang_rice_terrace_ubud_bali.jpg/330px-1_Tegalalang_rice_terrace_ubud_bali.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/1_Tegalalang_rice_terrace_ubud_bali.jpg/440px-1_Tegalalang_rice_terrace_ubud_bali.jpg 2x"></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:1_Tegalalang_rice_terrace_ubud_bali.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.23wmf6/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt=""></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Subak_(irrigation)" title="Subak (irrigation)">Subak</a> irrigation system</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The largest city is the provincial capital, <a href="/wiki/Denpasar" title="Denpasar">Denpasar</a>, near the southern coast. Its population is around 491,500 (2002). Bali's second-largest city is the old colonial capital, <a href="/wiki/Singaraja" title="Singaraja">Singaraja</a>, which is located on the north coast and is home to around 100,000 people. Other important cities include the beach resort, <a href="/wiki/Kuta" title="Kuta">Kuta</a>, which is practically part of Denpasar's urban area, and <a href="/wiki/Ubud" title="Ubud">Ubud</a>, situated at the north of Denpasar, is the island's cultural centre.</p>
<p>Three small islands lie to the immediate south east and all are administratively part of the <a href="/wiki/Klungkung" title="Klungkung" class="mw-redirect">Klungkung</a> regency of Bali: <a href="/wiki/Nusa_Penida" title="Nusa Penida">Nusa Penida</a>, <a href="/wiki/Nusa_Lembongan" title="Nusa Lembongan">Nusa Lembongan</a> and <a href="/w/index.php?title=Nusa_Ceningan&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Nusa Ceningan (page does not exist)">Nusa Ceningan</a>. These islands are separated from Bali by the Badung Strait.</p>
<p>To the east, the <a href="/wiki/Lombok_Strait" title="Lombok Strait">Lombok Strait</a> separates Bali from <a href="/wiki/Lombok" title="Lombok">Lombok</a> and marks the <a href="/wiki/Biogeography" title="Biogeography">biogeographical</a> division between the fauna of the <a href="/wiki/Indomalaya" title="Indomalaya" class="mw-redirect">Indomalayan</a> <a href="/wiki/Ecozone" title="Ecozone">ecozone</a> and the distinctly different fauna of <a href="/wiki/Australasia" title="Australasia">Australasia</a>. The transition is known as the <a href="/wiki/Wallace_Line" title="Wallace Line">Wallace Line</a>, named after <a href="/wiki/Alfred_Russel_Wallace" title="Alfred Russel Wallace">Alfred Russel Wallace</a>, who first proposed a transition zone between these two major <a href="/wiki/Biome" title="Biome">biomes</a>. When sea levels dropped during the <a href="/wiki/Quaternary_glaciation" title="Quaternary glaciation">Pleistocene ice age</a>, Bali was connected to Java and <a href="/wiki/Sumatra" title="Sumatra">Sumatra</a> and to the mainland of Asia and shared the Asian fauna, but the deep water of the Lombok Strait continued to keep Lombok Island and the <a href="/wiki/Lesser_Sunda_Islands" title="Lesser Sunda Islands">Lesser Sunda archipelago</a> isolated.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Ecology">Ecology</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Ecology">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<table class="metadata plainlinks ambox ambox-content ambox-Refimprove" role="presentation">
<tbody><tr>
<td class="mbox-image">
<div style="width:52px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png" width="50" height="39" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/75px-Question_book-new.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/100px-Question_book-new.svg.png 2x"></a></div>
</td>
<td class="mbox-text"><span class="mbox-text-span">This section <b>needs additional citations for <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title="Wikipedia:Verifiability">verification</a></b>. <span class="hide-when-compact">Please help <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit">improve this article</a> by <a href="/wiki/Help:Introduction_to_referencing/1" title="Help:Introduction to referencing/1">adding citations to reliable sources</a>. Unsourced material may be challenged and removed.</span> <small><i>(October 2012)</i></small></span></td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Bali_Mynah_-_Houston_Zoo.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Bali_Mynah_-_Houston_Zoo.jpg/170px-Bali_Mynah_-_Houston_Zoo.jpg" width="170" height="217" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Bali_Mynah_-_Houston_Zoo.jpg/255px-Bali_Mynah_-_Houston_Zoo.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Bali_Mynah_-_Houston_Zoo.jpg/340px-Bali_Mynah_-_Houston_Zoo.jpg 2x"></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Bali_Mynah_-_Houston_Zoo.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.23wmf6/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt=""></a></div>
The <a href="/wiki/Bali_Starling" title="Bali Starling" class="mw-redirect">Bali Starling</a> is found only on Bali and is critically endangered.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Bali lies just to the west of the <a href="/wiki/Wallace_Line" title="Wallace Line">Wallace Line</a>, and thus has a fauna that is Asian in character, with very little Australasian influence, and has more in common with Java than with Lombok.<sup class="Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2012)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> An exception is the <a href="/wiki/Yellow-crested_Cockatoo" title="Yellow-crested Cockatoo">Yellow-crested Cockatoo</a>, a member of a primarily Australasian family. There are around 280 species of birds, including the critically endangered <a href="/wiki/Bali_Starling" title="Bali Starling" class="mw-redirect">Bali Starling</a>, which is <a href="/wiki/Endemism" title="Endemism">endemic</a>. Others Include <a href="/wiki/Barn_Swallow" title="Barn Swallow">Barn Swallow</a>, <a href="/wiki/Black-naped_Oriole" title="Black-naped Oriole">Black-naped Oriole</a>, <a href="/wiki/Black_Racket-tailed_Treepie" title="Black Racket-tailed Treepie" class="mw-redirect">Black Racket-tailed Treepie</a>, <a href="/wiki/Crested_Serpent-eagle" title="Crested Serpent-eagle" class="mw-redirect">Crested Serpent-eagle</a>, <a href="/wiki/Crested_Treeswift" title="Crested Treeswift">Crested Treeswift</a>, <a href="/wiki/Dollarbird" title="Dollarbird">Dollarbird</a>, <a href="/wiki/Java_Sparrow" title="Java Sparrow">Java Sparrow</a>, <a href="/wiki/Lesser_Adjutant" title="Lesser Adjutant">Lesser Adjutant</a>, <a href="/wiki/Long-tailed_Shrike" title="Long-tailed Shrike">Long-tailed Shrike</a>, <a href="/wiki/Milky_Stork" title="Milky Stork">Milky Stork</a>, <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Swallow" title="Pacific Swallow">Pacific Swallow</a>, <a href="/wiki/Red-rumped_Swallow" title="Red-rumped Swallow">Red-rumped Swallow</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sacred_Kingfisher" title="Sacred Kingfisher">Sacred Kingfisher</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sea_eagle_(bird)" title="Sea eagle (bird)" class="mw-redirect">Sea Eagle</a>, <a href="/wiki/Woodswallow" title="Woodswallow">Woodswallow</a>, <a href="/wiki/Savanna_Nightjar" title="Savanna Nightjar">Savanna Nightjar</a>, <a href="/wiki/Stork-billed_Kingfisher" title="Stork-billed Kingfisher">Stork-billed Kingfisher</a>, <a href="/wiki/Yellow-vented_Bulbul" title="Yellow-vented Bulbul">Yellow-vented Bulbul</a>, <a href="/wiki/Great_Egret" title="Great Egret">White Heron</a>, <a href="/wiki/Great_Egret" title="Great Egret">Great Egret</a>.</p>
<p>Until the early 20th century, Bali was home to several large mammals: the wild <a href="/wiki/Banteng" title="Banteng">Banteng</a>, <a href="/wiki/Leopard" title="Leopard">leopard</a> and the endemic <a href="/wiki/Bali_tiger" title="Bali tiger">Bali tiger</a>. The Banteng still occurs in its domestic form, whereas leopards are found only in neighboring Java, and the Bali tiger is extinct. The last definite record of a tiger on Bali dates from 1937, when one was shot, though the subspecies may have survived until the 1940s or 1950s.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20"><span>[</span>20<span>]</span></a></sup> The relatively small size of the island, conflict with humans, poaching and habitat reduction drove the Bali tiger to extinction. This was the smallest and rarest of all tiger subspecies and was never caught on film or displayed in zoos, whereas few skins or bones remain in museums around the world. Today, the largest mammals are the <a href="/wiki/Javan_Rusa" title="Javan Rusa" class="mw-redirect">Javan Rusa</a> deer and the <a href="/wiki/Wild_Boar" title="Wild Boar" class="mw-redirect">Wild Boar</a>.<sup class="Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2012)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> A second, smaller species of deer, the <a href="/wiki/Indian_Muntjac" title="Indian Muntjac" class="mw-redirect">Indian Muntjac</a>, also occurs. <a href="/wiki/Saltwater_crocodile" title="Saltwater crocodile">Saltwater crocodiles</a> were once present on the island, but became locally extinct sometime during the last century.<sup class="Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2012)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Monkey_at_Ulu_Watu_Temple.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f1/Monkey_at_Ulu_Watu_Temple.jpg/220px-Monkey_at_Ulu_Watu_Temple.jpg" width="220" height="159" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f1/Monkey_at_Ulu_Watu_Temple.jpg/330px-Monkey_at_Ulu_Watu_Temple.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f1/Monkey_at_Ulu_Watu_Temple.jpg/440px-Monkey_at_Ulu_Watu_Temple.jpg 2x"></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Monkey_at_Ulu_Watu_Temple.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.23wmf6/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt=""></a></div>
Monkey at Ulu Watu Temple</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><a href="/wiki/Squirrel" title="Squirrel">Squirrels</a> are quite commonly encountered, less often is the <a href="/wiki/Asian_Palm_Civet" title="Asian Palm Civet" class="mw-redirect">Asian Palm Civet</a>, which is also kept in coffee farms to produce <a href="/wiki/Kopi_Luwak" title="Kopi Luwak">Kopi Luwak</a>. <a href="/wiki/Bat" title="Bat">Bats</a> are well represented, perhaps the most famous place to encounter them remaining the Goa Lawah (Temple of the Bats) where they are worshipped by the locals and also constitute a tourist attraction. They also occur in other cave temples, for instance at Gangga Beach. Two species of <a href="/wiki/Old_World_monkey" title="Old World monkey">monkey</a> occur. The <a href="/wiki/Crab-eating_Macaque" title="Crab-eating Macaque" class="mw-redirect">Crab-eating Macaque</a>, known locally as "kera", is quite common around human settlements and temples, where it becomes accustomed to being fed by humans, particularly in any of the three "monkey forest" temples, such as the popular one in the <a href="/wiki/Ubud" title="Ubud">Ubud</a> area. They are also quite often kept as pets by locals. The second monkey, endemic to Java and some surrounding islands such as Bali, is far rarer and more elusive is the <a href="/wiki/Javan_Langur" title="Javan Langur" class="mw-redirect">Javan Langur</a>, locally known as "lutung". They occur in few places apart from the <a href="/wiki/Bali_Barat_National_Park" title="Bali Barat National Park" class="mw-redirect">Bali Barat National Park</a>. They are born an orange colour, though by their first year they would have already changed to a more blackish colouration.<sup class="Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2012)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> In Java however, there is more of a tendency for this species to retain its juvenile orange colour into adulthood, and so you can see a mixture of black and orange monkeys together as a family. Other rarer mammals include the <a href="/wiki/Leopard_Cat" title="Leopard Cat" class="mw-redirect">Leopard Cat</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sunda_Pangolin" title="Sunda Pangolin" class="mw-redirect">Sunda Pangolin</a> and <a href="/wiki/Black_Giant_Squirrel" title="Black Giant Squirrel" class="mw-redirect">Black Giant Squirrel</a>.</p>
<p>Snakes include the <a href="/wiki/King_Cobra" title="King Cobra" class="mw-redirect">King Cobra</a> and <a href="/wiki/Reticulated_Python" title="Reticulated Python" class="mw-redirect">Reticulated Python</a>. The <a href="/wiki/Water_Monitor" title="Water Monitor" class="mw-redirect">Water Monitor</a> can grow to at least 1.5&nbsp;m (4.9&nbsp;ft) in length and 50&nbsp;kg (110&nbsp;lb)<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21"><span>[</span>21<span>]</span></a></sup> and can move quickly.</p>
<p>The rich coral reefs around the coast, particularly around popular diving spots such as <a href="/wiki/Tulamben" title="Tulamben">Tulamben</a>, <a href="/w/index.php?title=Amed_(Bali)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Amed (Bali) (page does not exist)">Amed</a>, Menjangan or neighboring <a href="/wiki/Nusa_Penida" title="Nusa Penida">Nusa Penida</a>, host a wide range of marine life, for instance <a href="/wiki/Hawksbill_Turtle" title="Hawksbill Turtle" class="mw-redirect">Hawksbill Turtle</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mola_mola" title="Mola mola" class="mw-redirect">Giant Sunfish</a>, <a href="/wiki/Manta_ray" title="Manta ray">Giant Manta Ray</a>, <a href="/wiki/Giant_moray" title="Giant moray">Giant Moray Eel</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bumphead_Parrotfish" title="Bumphead Parrotfish" class="mw-redirect">Bumphead Parrotfish</a>, <a href="/wiki/Hammerhead_Shark" title="Hammerhead Shark" class="mw-redirect">Hammerhead Shark</a>, <a href="/wiki/Grey_reef_shark" title="Grey reef shark">Reef Shark</a>, <a href="/wiki/Barracuda" title="Barracuda">barracuda</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Sea_snake" title="Sea snake" class="mw-redirect">sea snakes</a>. Dolphins are commonly encountered on the north coast near <a href="/wiki/Singaraja" title="Singaraja">Singaraja</a> and <a href="/wiki/Lovina" title="Lovina" class="mw-redirect">Lovina</a>.</p>
<p>A team of scientists conducted a survey from 29 April 2011 to 11 May 2011 at 33 sea sites around Bali. They discovered 952 species of reef fish of which 8 were new discoveries at <a href="/w/index.php?title=Pemuteran&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Pemuteran (page does not exist)">Pemuteran</a>, <a href="/w/index.php?title=Gilimanuk&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Gilimanuk (page does not exist)">Gilimanuk</a>, <a href="/wiki/Nusa_Dua" title="Nusa Dua">Nusa Dua</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tulamben" title="Tulamben">Tulamben</a> and <a href="/wiki/Candidasa" title="Candidasa" class="mw-redirect">Candidasa</a>, and 393 coral species, including two new ones at <a href="/wiki/Padangbai" title="Padangbai">Padangbai</a> and between Padangbai and <a href="/w/index.php?title=Amed_(Bali)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Amed (Bali) (page does not exist)">Amed</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22"><span>[</span>22<span>]</span></a></sup> The average coverage level of healthy coral was 36% (better than in <a href="/wiki/Raja_Ampat" title="Raja Ampat" class="mw-redirect">Raja Ampat</a> and <a href="/wiki/Halmahera" title="Halmahera">Halmahera</a> by 29% or in <a href="/wiki/Fakfak" title="Fakfak">Fakfak</a> and <a href="/wiki/Kaimana" title="Kaimana">Kaimana</a> by 25%) with the highest coverage found in <a href="/w/index.php?title=Gili_Selang&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Gili Selang (page does not exist)">Gili Selang</a> and <a href="/w/index.php?title=Gili_Mimpang&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Gili Mimpang (page does not exist)">Gili Mimpang</a> in <a href="/wiki/Candidasa" title="Candidasa" class="mw-redirect">Candidasa</a>, <a href="/wiki/Karangasem" title="Karangasem" class="mw-redirect">Karangasem</a> regency.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23"><span>[</span>23<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Many plants have been introduced by humans within the last centuries, particularly since the 20th century, making it sometimes hard to distinguish what plants are really native.<sup class="Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2012)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> Among the larger trees the most common are: <a href="/wiki/Banyan" title="Banyan">Banyan</a> trees, <a href="/wiki/Jackfruit" title="Jackfruit">Jackfruit</a>, <a href="/wiki/Coconut" title="Coconut">coconuts</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bamboo" title="Bamboo">bamboo</a> species, <a href="/wiki/Acacia" title="Acacia">acacia</a> trees and also endless rows of <a href="/wiki/Coconut" title="Coconut">coconuts</a> and banana species. Numerous flowers can be seen: <a href="/wiki/Hibiscus" title="Hibiscus">hibiscus</a>, <a href="/wiki/Frangipani" title="Frangipani" class="mw-redirect">frangipani</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bougainvillea" title="Bougainvillea">bougainvillea</a>, <a href="/wiki/Poinsettia" title="Poinsettia">poinsettia</a>, <a href="/wiki/Oleander" title="Oleander" class="mw-redirect">oleander</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jasmine" title="Jasmine">jasmine</a>, <a href="/wiki/Nymphaeaceae" title="Nymphaeaceae">water lily</a>, <a href="/wiki/Nelumbo" title="Nelumbo">lotus</a>, <a href="/wiki/Rose" title="Rose">roses</a>, <a href="/wiki/Begonia" title="Begonia">begonias</a>, orchids and <a href="/wiki/Hydrangea" title="Hydrangea">hydrangeas</a> exist. On higher grounds that receive more moisture, for instance around <a href="/wiki/Kintamani,_Bali" title="Kintamani, Bali">Kintamani</a>, certain species of <a href="/wiki/Fern" title="Fern">fern</a> trees, <a href="/wiki/Mushroom" title="Mushroom">mushrooms</a> and even <a href="/wiki/Pine" title="Pine">pine</a> trees thrive well. Rice comes in many varieties. Other plants with agricultural value include: <a href="/wiki/Salak" title="Salak">salak</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mangosteen" title="Mangosteen" class="mw-redirect">mangosteen</a>, <a href="/wiki/Maize" title="Maize">corn</a>, Kintamani orange, coffee and <a href="/wiki/Water_spinach" title="Water spinach" class="mw-redirect">water spinach</a>.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Environment">Environment</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Environment">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Some of the worst erosion has occurred in <a href="/w/index.php?title=Lebih_Beach&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Lebih Beach (page does not exist)">Lebih Beach</a>, where up to 7 meters of land is lost every year. Decades ago, this beach was used for holy pilgrimages with more than 10,000 people, but they have now moved to <a href="/w/index.php?title=Masceti_Beach&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Masceti Beach (page does not exist)">Masceti Beach</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24"><span>[</span>24<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>From ranked third in previous review, in 2010 Bali got score 99.65 of Indonesia's environmental quality index and the highest of all the 33 provinces. The score measured 3 water quality parameters: the level of <a href="/wiki/Total_suspended_solids" title="Total suspended solids">total suspended solids</a> (TSS), <a href="/wiki/Dissolved_oxygen" title="Dissolved oxygen" class="mw-redirect">dissolved oxygen</a> (DO) and <a href="/wiki/Chemical_oxygen_demand" title="Chemical oxygen demand">chemical oxygen demand</a> (COD).<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25"><span>[</span>25<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Because of over-exploitation by the tourist industry which converse massive land, 200 out of 400 rivers on the island have dried up and based on research, the southern part of Bali would face a water shortage up to 2,500 liters of clean water per second by 2015.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26"><span>[</span>26<span>]</span></a></sup> To ease the shortage, the central government plans to build a water catchment and processing facility at Petanu River in Gianyar. The 300 liters capacity of water per second will be channeled to Denpasar, Badung and Gianyar in 2013.<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27"><span>[</span>27<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Administrative_divisions">Administrative divisions</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Administrative divisions">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>The province is divided into 8 <a href="/wiki/Regencies_of_Indonesia" title="Regencies of Indonesia" class="mw-redirect">regencies</a> (<i>kabupaten</i>) and 1 <a href="/wiki/Cities_of_Indonesia" title="Cities of Indonesia" class="mw-redirect">city</a> (<i>kota</i>). These are:</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Economy">Economy</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Economy">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Three decades ago, the Balinese economy was largely agriculture-based in terms of both output and employment. Tourism is now the largest single industry in terms of income, and as a result, Bali is one of Indonesia's wealthiest regions. About 80% of Bali's economy depends on tourism;<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28"><span>[</span>28<span>]</span></a></sup> Note: non-referenced&nbsp;% in the article: in fact a great number of the population still lives thanks to agriculture although this situation is changing rapidly. By end of June 2011, <a href="/wiki/Non-performing_loan" title="Non-performing loan">non-performing loan</a> of all banks in Bali were 2.23%, lower than the average of Indonesian banking industry non-performing loan (about 5%).<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29"><span>[</span>29<span>]</span></a></sup> The economy, however, suffered significantly as a result of the terrorist bombings <a href="/wiki/2002_Bali_bombing" title="2002 Bali bombing" class="mw-redirect">2002</a> and <a href="/wiki/2005_Bali_bombing" title="2005 Bali bombing" class="mw-redirect">2005</a>. The tourism industry has since recovered from these events.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Agriculture">Agriculture</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Agriculture">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Although tourism produces the GDP's largest output, agriculture is still the island's biggest employer;<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30"><span>[</span>30<span>]</span></a></sup><sup class="Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2007)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> most notably rice cultivation. Crops grown in smaller amounts include fruit, vegetables, <i><a href="/wiki/Coffea_arabica" title="Coffea arabica">Coffea arabica</a></i> and other <a href="/wiki/Cash_crop" title="Cash crop">cash</a> and subsistence crops.<sup class="Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2007)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> Fishing also provides a significant number of jobs. Bali is also famous for its <a href="/wiki/Artisan" title="Artisan">artisans</a> who produce a vast array of handicrafts, including <a href="/wiki/Batik" title="Batik">batik</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ikat" title="Ikat">ikat</a> <a href="/wiki/Bali_Nusra_Tangi" title="Bali Nusra Tangi">cloth and clothing</a>, <a href="/wiki/Woodworking" title="Woodworking">wooden carvings</a>, stone carvings, painted art and silverware. Notably, individual villages typically adopt a single product, such as wind chimes or wooden furniture.</p>
<p>The Arabica coffee production region is the highland region of Kintamani near <a href="/wiki/Mount_Batur" title="Mount Batur">Mount Batur</a>. Generally, Balinese coffee is processed using the wet method. This results in a sweet, soft coffee with good consistency. Typical flavors include lemon and other citrus notes.<sup id="cite_ref-SCAI_31-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SCAI-31"><span>[</span>31<span>]</span></a></sup> Many coffee farmers in Kintamani are members of a traditional farming system called <a href="/wiki/Subak_(irrigation)" title="Subak (irrigation)">Subak Abian</a>, which is based on the <a href="/wiki/Hindu" title="Hindu">Hindu</a> philosophy of "Tri Hita Karana". According to this philosophy, the three causes of happiness are good relations with God, other people and the environment. The Subak Abian system is ideally suited to the production of fair trade and organic coffee production. Arabica coffee from Kintamani is the first product in Indonesia to request a <a href="/wiki/Geographical_Indication" title="Geographical Indication" class="mw-redirect">Geographical Indication</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-BaliKintamani_32-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BaliKintamani-32"><span>[</span>32<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Tourism">Tourism</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Tourism">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Bali_canyoning.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/27/Bali_canyoning.jpg/220px-Bali_canyoning.jpg" width="220" height="330" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/27/Bali_canyoning.jpg/330px-Bali_canyoning.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/27/Bali_canyoning.jpg/440px-Bali_canyoning.jpg 2x"></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">

</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:1_pura_taman_ayun_bali_2011.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/1_pura_taman_ayun_bali_2011.jpg/220px-1_pura_taman_ayun_bali_2011.jpg" width="220" height="146" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/1_pura_taman_ayun_bali_2011.jpg/330px-1_pura_taman_ayun_bali_2011.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/1_pura_taman_ayun_bali_2011.jpg/440px-1_pura_taman_ayun_bali_2011.jpg 2x"></a>

</div>
</div>
<table class="metadata plainlinks ambox ambox-content ambox-Refimprove" role="presentation">
<tbody><tr>
<td class="mbox-image">
<div style="width:52px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png" width="50" height="39" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/75px-Question_book-new.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/100px-Question_book-new.svg.png 2x"></a></div>

</tr>
</tbody></table>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Arjuna_statue.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Arjuna_statue.JPG/170px-Arjuna_statue.JPG" width="170" height="255" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Arjuna_statue.JPG/255px-Arjuna_statue.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Arjuna_statue.JPG/340px-Arjuna_statue.JPG 2x"></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Arjuna_statue.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.23wmf6/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt=""></a></div>
A statue of Arjuna on a street in Bali</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Tourism_industry" title="Tourism industry" class="mw-redirect">tourism industry</a> is primarily focused in the south, while significant in the other parts of the island as well. The main tourist locations are the town of <a href="/wiki/Kuta" title="Kuta">Kuta</a> (with its beach), and its outer suburbs of Legian and <a href="/wiki/Seminyak" title="Seminyak">Seminyak</a> (which were once independent townships), the east coast town of <a href="/wiki/Sanur_(Bali)" title="Sanur (Bali)" class="mw-redirect">Sanur</a> (once the only tourist hub), in the center of the island <a href="/wiki/Ubud" title="Ubud">Ubud</a>, to the south of the <a href="/wiki/Ngurah_Rai_International_Airport" title="Ngurah Rai International Airport">Ngurah Rai International Airport</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jimbaran" title="Jimbaran">Jimbaran</a>, and the newer development of <a href="/wiki/Nusa_Dua" title="Nusa Dua">Nusa Dua</a> and <a href="/wiki/Pecatu" title="Pecatu">Pecatu</a>.</p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/American_government" title="American government" class="mw-redirect">American government</a> lifted its travel warnings in 2008. The Australian government last issued an advice on Friday, 4 May 2012. The overall level of the advice was lowered to 'Exercise a high degree of caution'. The Swedish government issued a new warning on Sunday, 10 June 2012 because of one more tourist who has been killed by methanol poisoning.<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33"><span>[</span>33<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Kuta_Beach.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Kuta_Beach.JPG/220px-Kuta_Beach.JPG" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Kuta_Beach.JPG/330px-Kuta_Beach.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Kuta_Beach.JPG/440px-Kuta_Beach.JPG 2x"></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Kuta_Beach.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.23wmf6/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt=""></a></div>
Kuta Beach is a popular tourist spot in Bali</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>An offshoot of tourism is the growing real estate industry. Bali real estate has been rapidly developing in the main tourist areas of Kuta, Legian, Seminyak and Oberoi. Most recently, high-end 5 star projects are under development on the Bukit peninsula, on the south side of the island. Million dollar villas are being developed along the cliff sides of south Bali, commanding panoramic ocean views. Foreign and domestic (many Jakarta individuals and companies are fairly active) investment into other areas of the island also continues to grow. Land prices, despite the worldwide economic crisis, have remained stable.</p>
<p>In the last half of 2008, Indonesia's currency had dropped approximately 30% against the US dollar, providing many overseas visitors value for their currencies. Visitor arrivals for 2009 were forecast to drop 8% (which would be higher than 2007 levels), due to the worldwide economic crisis which has also affected the global tourist industry, but not due to any travel warnings.</p>
<p>Bali's tourism economy survived the terrorist bombings of 2002 and 2005, and the tourism industry has in fact slowly recovered and surpassed its pre-terrorist bombing levels; the longterm trend has been a steady increase of visitor arrivals. In 2010, Bali received 2.57 million foreign tourists, which surpassed the target of 2.02.3 million tourists. The average occupancy of starred hotels achieved 65%, so the island is still able to accommodate tourists for some years without any addition of new rooms/hotels,<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34"><span>[</span>34<span>]</span></a></sup> although at the peak season some of them are fully booked.</p>
<p>Bali received the Best Island award from <a href="/wiki/Travel_and_Leisure" title="Travel and Leisure" class="mw-redirect">Travel and Leisure</a> in 2010.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35"><span>[</span>35<span>]</span></a></sup> The island of Bali won because of its attractive surroundings (both mountain and coastal areas), diverse tourist attractions, excellent international and local restaurants, and the friendliness of the local people. According to BBC Travel released in 2011, Bali is one of the World's Best Islands, rank in second after <a href="/wiki/Greece" title="Greece">Greece</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36"><span>[</span>36<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>In August 2010, the film version of <a href="/wiki/Eat,_Pray,_Love" title="Eat, Pray, Love">Eat, Pray, Love</a> (EPL) was released in theaters. The movie was based on <a href="/wiki/Elizabeth_Gilbert" title="Elizabeth Gilbert">Elizabeth Gilbert</a>'s best-selling memoir of the same name. It took place at Ubud and Padang-Padang Beach at Bali. The 2006 book, which spent 57 weeks at the No. 1 spot on the New York Times paperback nonfiction best-seller list, had already fueled a boom in EPL tourism in Ubud, the hill town and cultural and tourist center that was the focus of Gilbert's quest for balance through traditional spirituality and healing that leads to love.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37"><span>[</span>37<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Since 2011, China has displaced Japan as the second-largest supplier of tourists to Bali, while Australia still tops the list. Chinese tourists increased by 17% from last year due to the impact of <a href="/wiki/ACFTA" title="ACFTA" class="mw-redirect">ACFTA</a> and new direct flights to Bali.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38"><span>[</span>38<span>]</span></a></sup> In January 2012, Chinese tourists year on year (yoy) increased by 222.18% compared to January 2011, while Japanese tourists declined by 23.54% yoy.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39"><span>[</span>39<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Bali reported that it has 2.88 million foreign tourists and 5 million domestic tourists in 2012, marginally surpassing the expectations of 2.8 million foreign tourists. Forecasts for 2013 are at 3.1 million.<sup id="cite_ref-balitourism_40-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-balitourism-40"><span>[</span>40<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Based on <a href="/wiki/Bank_Indonesia" title="Bank Indonesia">Bank Indonesia</a> survey in May 2013, 34.39 percent of tourists are upper-middle class with spending between $1,286 to $5,592 and dominated by Australia, France, China, Germany and the US with some China tourists move from low spending before to higher spending currently. While 30.26 percent are middle class with spending between $662 to $1,285.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41"><span>[</span>41<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Transportation">Transportation</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Transportation">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<table class="metadata plainlinks ambox ambox-content ambox-Update" role="presentation">
<tbody><tr>
<td class="mbox-image">
<div style="width:52px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Ambox_current_red.svg" class="image"><img alt="Ambox current red.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Ambox_current_red.svg/42px-Ambox_current_red.svg.png" width="42" height="34" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Ambox_current_red.svg/63px-Ambox_current_red.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Ambox_current_red.svg/84px-Ambox_current_red.svg.png 2x"></a></div>
</td>
<td class="mbox-text"><span class="mbox-text-span">This section is <b>outdated</b>. <span class="hide-when-compact">Please update this article to reflect recent events or newly available information.</span> <small><i>(December 2012)</i></small></span></td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Bali_moped_col.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Bali_moped_col.jpg/220px-Bali_moped_col.jpg" width="220" height="205" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Bali_moped_col.jpg/330px-Bali_moped_col.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Bali_moped_col.jpg/440px-Bali_moped_col.jpg 2x"></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Bali_moped_col.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.23wmf6/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt=""></a></div>
A major form of transport in Bali is the <a href="/wiki/Moped" title="Moped">Moped</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Ngurah_Rai_Airport" title="Ngurah Rai Airport" class="mw-redirect">Ngurah Rai International Airport</a> is located near Jimbaran, on the <a href="/wiki/Isthmus" title="Isthmus" class="mw-redirect">isthmus</a> at the southernmost part of the island. <a href="/wiki/Lt.Col._Wisnu_Airfield" title="Lt.Col. Wisnu Airfield" class="mw-redirect">Lt.Col. Wisnu Airfield</a> is found in north-west Bali.</p>
<p>A coastal road circles the island, and three major two-lane arteries cross the central mountains at passes reaching to 1,750m in height (at Penelokan). The Ngurah Rai Bypass is a four-lane expressway that partly encircles Denpasar and enables cars to travel quickly in the heavily populated south. Bali has no railway lines yet.</p>
<p>December 2010: Government of Indonesia has invited investors to build Tanah Ampo Cruise Terminal at <a href="/wiki/Karangasem" title="Karangasem" class="mw-redirect">Karangasem</a>, Bali amounted $30&nbsp;million.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42"><span>[</span>42<span>]</span></a></sup> In 17 July 2011 the first cruise ship (<a href="/wiki/Sun_Princess" title="Sun Princess">Sun Princess</a>) will anchor about 400 meters away from the wharf of Tanah Ampo harbor. The current pier is only 154 meters and will eventually be 300 to 350 meters to accommodate international cruise ships. The harbor would be safer than Benoa and has a scenic backdrop of a panoramic view of mountainous area with green rice fields.<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43"><span>[</span>43<span>]</span></a></sup> By December 2011 the auction process will be settled and Tanah Ampo is predicted to become the main hub for cruise ships in Indonesia by 2013.<sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44"><span>[</span>44<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>A Memorandum of Understanding has been signed by two ministers, Bali's Governor and <a href="/wiki/PT_Kereta_Api" title="PT Kereta Api">Indonesian Train Company</a> to build 565 kilometers of railway along the coast around the island. It should be operating by 2015.<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45"><span>[</span>45<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>On 16 March 2011 (Tanjung) Benoa port received the "Best Port Welcome 2010" award from London's "Dream World Cruise Destination" magazine.<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46"><span>[</span>46<span>]</span></a></sup> Government plans to expand the role of Benoa port as export-import port to boost Bali's trade and industry sector.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47"><span>[</span>47<span>]</span></a></sup> The Tourism and Creative Economy Ministry has confirmed that 306 cruise liners are heading for Indonesia in 2013 - an increase of 43 percent compared to the previous year. <sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48"><span>[</span>48<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>On May 2011, an integrated Areal Traffic Control System (ATCS) was implemented to reduce traffic jams at four crossing points: Ngurah Rai statue, Dewa Ruci Kuta crossing, Jimbaran crossing and Sanur crossing. ATCS is an integrated system connecting all traffic lights, CCTVs and other traffic signals with a monitoring office at the police headquarters. It has successfully been implemented in other ASEAN countries and will be implemented at other crossings in Bali.<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49"><span>[</span>49<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50"><span>[</span>50<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>On 21 December 2011 construction started on the Nusa Dua-Benoa-<a href="/wiki/Ngurah_Rai_International_Airport" title="Ngurah Rai International Airport">Ngurah Rai International Airport</a> toll road which will also provide a special lane for motorcycles. This has been done by seven state-owned enterprises led by PT Jasa Marga with 60% of shares. PT Jasa Marga Bali Tol will construct the 9.91 kilometers toll road (totally 12.7 kilometers with access road). The construction is estimated to cost Rp.2.49 trillion ($273.9 million). The project goes through 2 kilometers of mangrove forest and through 2.3 kilometers of beach, both within 5.4 hectares area. The elevated toll road is built over the mangrove forest on 18,000 concrete pillars which occupied 2 hectares of mangroves forest. It compensated by new planting of 300,000 mangrove trees along the road. On 21 December 2011 the Dewa Ruci 450 meters underpass has also started on the busy Dewa Ruci junction near Bali Kuta Galeria with an estimated cost of Rp136 billion ($14.9 million) from the state budget.<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51"><span>[</span>51<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52"><span>[</span>52<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53"><span>[</span>53<span>]</span></a></sup> On September 23, 2013, the <a href="/wiki/Bali_Mandara_Toll_Road" title="Bali Mandara Toll Road">Bali Mandara Toll Road</a> is opened and the Dewa Ruci Junction (Simpang Siur) underpass is opened before. Both are ease the heavy traffic congestion.<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54"><span>[</span>54<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>To solve chronic traffic problems, the province will also build a toll road connecting Serangan with <a href="/wiki/Tohpati" title="Tohpati">Tohpati</a>, a toll road connecting Kuta, Denpasar and Tohpati and a flyover connecting Kuta and Ngurah Rai Airport.<sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55"><span>[</span>55<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Demographics">Demographics</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Demographics">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
