<p>The population of Bali was 3,890,757 as of the 2010 Census. There are an estimated 30,000 expatriates living in Bali.<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57"><span>[</span>57<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Ethnic_origins">Ethnic origins</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Ethnic origins">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>A DNA study in 2005 by Karafet et al.<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58"><span>[</span>58<span>]</span></a></sup> found that 12% of Balinese <a href="/wiki/Y-chromosome" title="Y-chromosome" class="mw-redirect">Y-chromosomes</a> are of likely <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">Indian</a> origin, while 84% are of likely <a href="/wiki/Austronesian" title="Austronesian" class="mw-redirect">Austronesian</a> origin, and 2% of likely <a href="/wiki/Melanesian" title="Melanesian" class="mw-redirect">Melanesian</a> origin. The study does not correlate the DNA samples to the Balinese caste system.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Caste_system">Caste system</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Caste system">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="rellink relarticle mainarticle">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Balinese_caste_system" title="Balinese caste system">Balinese caste system</a></div>
<p>Bali has a caste system based on the <a href="/wiki/Indian_caste_system" title="Indian caste system" class="mw-redirect">Indian Hindu model</a>, with four castes:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Shudra" title="Shudra">Shudras</a> - <a href="/wiki/Peasant" title="Peasant">peasants</a> constituting close to 93% of Bali's population.<sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59"><span>[</span>59<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Wesias (<a href="/wiki/Vaishya" title="Vaishya">Vaishyas</a>) - the caste of merchants and administrative officials</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Balinese_Kshatriya" title="Balinese Kshatriya">Ksatrias</a> (<a href="/wiki/Kshatriya" title="Kshatriya">Kshatriyas</a>) - the kingly and <a href="/wiki/Warrior" title="Warrior">warrior</a> caste</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Brahmin" title="Brahmin">Brahmins</a> - holy men and <a href="/wiki/Priest" title="Priest">priests</a></li>
</ul>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Religion">Religion</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Religion">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mother_Temple_of_Besakih.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/Mother_Temple_of_Besakih.jpg/220px-Mother_Temple_of_Besakih.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/Mother_Temple_of_Besakih.jpg/330px-Mother_Temple_of_Besakih.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/Mother_Temple_of_Besakih.jpg/440px-Mother_Temple_of_Besakih.jpg 2x"></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Mother_Temple_of_Besakih.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.23wmf6/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt=""></a></div>
The <a href="/wiki/Mother_Temple_of_Besakih" title="Mother Temple of Besakih">Mother Temple of Besakih</a>, one of Bali's most significant <a href="/wiki/Hindu" title="Hindu">Hindu</a> temples.</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Ubud_Cremation_Procession_1.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Ubud_Cremation_Procession_1.jpg/220px-Ubud_Cremation_Procession_1.jpg" width="220" height="176" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Ubud_Cremation_Procession_1.jpg/330px-Ubud_Cremation_Procession_1.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Ubud_Cremation_Procession_1.jpg/440px-Ubud_Cremation_Procession_1.jpg 2x"></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Ubud_Cremation_Procession_1.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.23wmf6/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt=""></a></div>
A religious procession</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Unlike most of Muslim-majority Indonesia, about 83.5% of Bali's population adheres to <a href="/wiki/Balinese_Hinduism" title="Balinese Hinduism">Balinese Hinduism</a>, formed as a combination of existing <a href="/wiki/Balinese_mythology" title="Balinese mythology">local beliefs</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hindu" title="Hindu">Hindu</a> influences from mainland Southeast Asia and South Asia. Minority religions include Islam (13.3%), Christianity (1.7%), and <a href="/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">Buddhism</a> (0.5%).<sup id="cite_ref-census2010_4-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-census2010-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> These figures do not include immigrants from other parts of Indonesia.</p>
<p>When Islam surpassed <a href="/wiki/Hinduism" title="Hinduism">Hinduism</a> in <a href="/wiki/Java" title="Java">Java</a> (16th century), Bali became a refuge for many Hindus. Balinese Hinduism is an amalgam in which gods and demigods are worshipped together with Buddhist heroes, the spirits of ancestors, indigenous agricultural deities and sacred places. Religion as it is practiced in Bali is a composite belief system that embraces not only theology, philosophy, and mythology, but ancestor worship, animism and magic. It pervades nearly every aspect of traditional life. <a href="/wiki/Caste" title="Caste">Caste</a> is observed, though less strictly than in India. With an estimated 20,000 <a href="/wiki/Pura_(Balinese_temple)" title="Pura (Balinese temple)" class="mw-redirect">puras (temples)</a> and shrines, Bali is known as the "Island of a Thousand Puras", or "Island of the Gods".<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60"><span>[</span>60<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Balinese Hinduism has roots in Indian Hinduism and in Buddhism, and adopted the animistic traditions of the indigenous people. This influence strengthened the belief that the gods and goddesses are present in all things. Every element of nature, therefore, possesses its own power, which reflects the power of the gods. A rock, tree, dagger, or woven cloth is a potential home for spirits whose energy can be directed for good or evil. Balinese Hinduism is deeply interwoven with art and ritual. Ritualizing states of self-control are a notable feature of religious expression among the people, who for this reason have become famous for their graceful and decorous behavior.<sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61"><span>[</span>61<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Apart from the majority of Balinese Hindus, there also exist <a href="/wiki/Chinese_Indonesian" title="Chinese Indonesian" class="mw-redirect">Chinese</a> immigrants whose traditions have melded with that of the locals. As a result, these Sino-Balinese not only embrace their original religion, which is a mixture of Buddhism, Christianity, Taoism and Confucianism, but also find a way to harmonize it with the local traditions. Hence, it is not uncommon to find local Sino-Balinese during the local temple's <i>odalan</i>. Moreover, Balinese Hindu priests are invited to perform rites alongside a Chinese priest in the event of the death of a Sino-Balinese.<sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-62"><span>[</span>62<span>]</span></a></sup> Nevertheless, the Sino-Balinese claim to embrace Buddhism for administrative purposes, such as their Identity Cards.<sup id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63"><span>[</span>63<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Language">Language</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Language">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p><a href="/wiki/Balinese_language" title="Balinese language">Balinese</a> and <a href="/wiki/Indonesian_language" title="Indonesian language">Indonesian</a> are the most widely spoken languages in Bali, and the vast majority of <a href="/wiki/Balinese_people" title="Balinese people">Balinese people</a> are <a href="/wiki/Bilingual" title="Bilingual" class="mw-redirect">bilingual</a> or <a href="/wiki/Trilingual" title="Trilingual" class="mw-redirect">trilingual</a>. The most common spoken language around the tourist areas is Indonesian, as many people in the tourist sector are not solely Balinese, but migrants from Java, Lombok, Sumatra, and other parts of Indonesia. There are several indigenous Balinese languages, but most Balinese can also use the most widely spoken option: modern common Balinese. The usage of different Balinese languages was traditionally determined by the <a href="/wiki/Balinese_caste_system" title="Balinese caste system">Balinese caste system</a> and by clan membership, but this tradition is diminishing. <a href="/wiki/Kawi_language" title="Kawi language">Kawi</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a> are also commonly used by some Hindu priests in Bali, for Hinduism literature was mostly written in Sanskrit.</p>
<p>English is a common third language (and the primary foreign language) of many Balinese, owing to the requirements of the <a href="/wiki/Tourism_industry" title="Tourism industry" class="mw-redirect">tourism industry</a>. Other foreign languages, such as Chinese, Japanese, <a href="/wiki/Korean_language" title="Korean language">Korean</a>, French or German are often used in multilingual signs for foreign tourists.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Culture">Culture</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Culture">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="rellink boilerplate seealso">See also: <a href="/wiki/Balinese_art" title="Balinese art">Balinese art</a>, <a href="/wiki/Music_of_Bali" title="Music of Bali">Music of Bali</a>,&nbsp;and <a href="/wiki/Balinese_cuisine" title="Balinese cuisine">Balinese cuisine</a></div>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Kecak.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/30/Kecak.JPG/220px-Kecak.JPG" width="220" height="167" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/30/Kecak.JPG/330px-Kecak.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/30/Kecak.JPG/440px-Kecak.JPG 2x"></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Kecak.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.23wmf6/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt=""></a></div>
A Kecak dance being performed at <a href="/wiki/Uluwatu" title="Uluwatu" class="mw-redirect">Uluwatu</a>, in Bali</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Bali is renowned for its diverse and sophisticated art forms, such as painting, sculpture, woodcarving, handcrafts, and performing arts. <a href="/wiki/Balinese_cuisine" title="Balinese cuisine">Balinese cuisine</a> is also distinctive. Balinese percussion orchestra music, known as <i><a href="/wiki/Gamelan" title="Gamelan">gamelan</a></i>, is highly developed and varied. Balinese performing arts often portray stories from Hindu epics such as the <a href="/wiki/Ramayana" title="Ramayana">Ramayana</a> but with heavy Balinese influence. Famous <a href="/wiki/Balinese_dance" title="Balinese dance">Balinese dances</a> include <i><a href="/wiki/Pendet" title="Pendet">pendet</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/Legong" title="Legong">legong</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/Baris_(dance)" title="Baris (dance)">baris</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/Topeng" title="Topeng" class="mw-redirect">topeng</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/Barong_(mythology)" title="Barong (mythology)">barong</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/Gamelan_gong_kebyar" title="Gamelan gong kebyar">gong keybar</a></i>, and <i><a href="/wiki/Kecak" title="Kecak">kecak</a></i> (the monkey dance). Bali boasts one of the most diverse and innovative performing arts cultures in the world, with paid performances at thousands of temple festivals, private ceremonies, or public shows.<sup id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-64"><span>[</span>64<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The Hindu New Year, <i><a href="/wiki/Nyepi" title="Nyepi">Nyepi</a></i>, is celebrated in the spring by a day of silence. On this day everyone stays at home and tourists are encouraged to remain in their hotels. On the day before New Year, large and colourful sculptures of <i>ogoh-ogoh</i> monsters are paraded and finally burned in the evening to drive away evil spirits. Other festivals throughout the year are specified by the Balinese <i><a href="/wiki/Pawukon" title="Pawukon" class="mw-redirect">pawukon</a></i> <a href="/wiki/Calendar" title="Calendar">calendrical</a> system.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Ubud_Cremation_4.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e9/Ubud_Cremation_4.jpg/170px-Ubud_Cremation_4.jpg" width="170" height="255" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e9/Ubud_Cremation_4.jpg/255px-Ubud_Cremation_4.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e9/Ubud_Cremation_4.jpg/340px-Ubud_Cremation_4.jpg 2x"></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Ubud_Cremation_4.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.23wmf6/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt=""></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Cremation" title="Cremation">Cremation</a> in <a href="/wiki/Ubud" title="Ubud">Ubud</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Celebrations are held for many occasions such as a tooth-filing (coming-of-age ritual), <a href="/wiki/Cremation" title="Cremation">cremation</a> or <i>odalan</i> (temple festival). One of the most important concepts that Balinese ceremonies have in common is that of <i>dsa kala patra</i>, which refers to how ritual performances must be appropriate in both the specific and general social context.<sup id="cite_ref-Herbst_65-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Herbst-65"><span>[</span>65<span>]</span></a></sup> Many of the ceremonial art forms such as <i><a href="/wiki/Wayang" title="Wayang">wayang kulit</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Topeng" title="Topeng" class="mw-redirect">topeng</a></i> are highly improvisatory, providing flexibility for the performer to adapt the performance to the current situation.<sup id="cite_ref-Foley_66-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Foley-66"><span>[</span>66<span>]</span></a></sup> Many celebrations call for a loud, boisterous atmosphere with lots of activity and the resulting aesthetic, <i>ram</i>, is distinctively Balinese. Often two or more <i><a href="/wiki/Music_of_Bali" title="Music of Bali">gamelan</a></i> ensembles will be performing well within earshot, and sometimes compete with each other in order to be heard. Likewise, the audience members talk amongst themselves, get up and walk around, or even cheer on the performance, which adds to the many layers of activity and the liveliness typical of <i>ram</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67"><span>[</span>67<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p><i>Kaja</i> and <i>kelod</i> are the Balinese equivalents of North and South, which refer to ones orientation between the island's largest mountain Gunung Agung (<i>kaja</i>), and the sea (<i>kelod</i>). In addition to spatial orientation, <i>kaja</i> and <i>kelod</i> have the connotation of good and evil; gods and ancestors are believed to live on the mountain whereas demons live in the sea. Buildings such as temples and residential homes are spatially oriented by having the most sacred spaces closest to the mountain and the unclean places nearest to the sea.<sup id="cite_ref-Herbst_65-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Herbst-65"><span>[</span>65<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68"><span>[</span>68<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Most temples have an inner courtyard and an outer courtyard which are arranged with the inner courtyard furthest <i>kaja</i>. These spaces serve as performance venues since most Balinese rituals are accompanied by any combination of music, dance and drama. The performances that take place in the inner courtyard are classified as <i>wali</i>, the most sacred rituals which are offerings exclusively for the gods, while the outer courtyard is where <i>bebali</i> ceremonies are held, which are intended for gods and people. Lastly, performances meant solely for the entertainment of humans take place outside the walls of the temple and are called <i>bali-balihan</i>. This three-tiered system of classification was standardized in 1971 by a committee of Balinese officials and artists in order to better protect the sanctity of the oldest and most sacred Balinese rituals from being performed for a paying audience.<sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69"><span>[</span>69<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Tourism, Bali's chief industry, has provided the island with a foreign audience that is eager to pay for entertainment, thus creating new performance opportunities and more demand for performers. The impact of <a href="/wiki/Tourism_in_indonesia" title="Tourism in indonesia" class="mw-redirect">tourism</a> is controversial since before it became integrated into the economy, the Balinese performing arts did not exist as a capitalist venture, and were not performed for entertainment outside of their respective ritual context. Since the 1930s sacred rituals such as the <i><a href="/wiki/Barong_(mythology)" title="Barong (mythology)">barong</a></i> <a href="/wiki/Balinese_dance" title="Balinese dance">dance</a> have been performed both in their original contexts, as well as exclusively for paying tourists. This has led to new versions of many of these performances which have developed according to the preferences of foreign audiences; some villages have a <i>barong</i> mask specifically for non-ritual performances as well as an older mask which is only used for sacred performances.<sup id="cite_ref-Sanger_70-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Sanger-70"><span>[</span>70<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Balinese society continues to revolve around each family's ancestral village, to which the cycle of life and religion is closely tied.<sup id="cite_ref-NYT_71-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYT-71"><span>[</span>71<span>]</span></a></sup> Coercive aspects of traditional society, such as <a href="/wiki/Customary_law" title="Customary law" class="mw-redirect">customary law</a> sanctions imposed by traditional authorities such as village councils (including "<a href="/wiki/Kasepekang" title="Kasepekang">kasepekang</a>", or <a href="/wiki/Shunning" title="Shunning">shunning</a>) have risen in importance as a consequence of the democratization and decentralization of Indonesia since 1998.<sup id="cite_ref-NYT_71-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYT-71"><span>[</span>71<span>]</span></a></sup></p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Sports">Sports</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Sports">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Bali was the host of <a href="/wiki/2008_Asian_Beach_Games" title="2008 Asian Beach Games">2008 Asian Beach Games</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72"><span>[</span>72<span>]</span></a></sup> It was the second time Indonesia hosted an Asia-level <a href="/wiki/Multi-sport_event" title="Multi-sport event">multi-sport event</a>, after <a href="/wiki/Jakarta" title="Jakarta">Jakarta</a> held the <a href="/wiki/1962_Asian_Games" title="1962 Asian Games">1962 Asian Games</a>.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Heritage_sites">Heritage sites</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Heritage sites">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>On June 2012, <a href="/wiki/Subak_(irrigation)" title="Subak (irrigation)">Subak</a>, the irrigation system for <a href="/wiki/Paddy_field" title="Paddy field">paddy fields</a> in Bali was enlisted as a <a href="/wiki/UNESCO_world_heritage_site" title="UNESCO world heritage site" class="mw-redirect">UNESCO world heritage site</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-73" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-73"><span>[</span>73<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Beauty_Pageant">Beauty Pageant</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bali&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Beauty Pageant">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Bali was the host of <a href="/wiki/Miss_World_2013" title="Miss World 2013">Miss World 2013</a>, It was the first time Indonesia hosted an International Beauty Pageant</p>
